My first mistake was opening Facebook on the bus to Austria. My second was opening instagram to look at more wedding photos of the person I went to college with.
.
I was in the Austrian countryside, in awe of this experience I get to have for myself and by myself, when I started comparing my life to others’.
.
It’s so easy to do, and that couple of minutes of comparison can take hours to come back from.
.
Here’s the thing that I came to: just because my journey is different than the “norm” doesn’t mean it’s worse.
.
I’m in Austria. Making gorgeous memories I’ll remember forever. This is special. This is important. This is a beautiful life.
.
The rest I’ll have. The kids and the partner. And I don’t “need” to have it now to have a meaningful, “right” life.
.
Same goes to you my friends 💚

YOU ARE NOT YOUR THOUGHTS 🙅🏼‍♀️ The saying “you are your thoughts” can be so scary for people with OCD who get scary unwanted thoughts repeatedly 🤯
.
Here’s the thing: thoughts are words in your mind. They’re not actions. They’re not threats. They’re not dangerous so long as we do nothing about them. They’re words that can be out of our control.
.
Thinking about a hamburger all day doesn’t make me a hamburger 🍔 (but I have one in my belly currently because I took an action and ate one for lunch — see the difference?!)
.
I loved joining @therapyforwomen on her podcast “Recovered-ish”! Y’all can listen at the link in my bio ❤️

Rewatching The Sound of Music for the first time since I was a kid brought me back to my life without OCD. 
.
It was so nostalgic and I saw the movie through the eyes of Alegra as a kid, before OCD. The alegra whose favorite character was Gretl because she was precious and I adored kids as a kid myself.
.
The Alegra who has loved children for as long as she can remember and knew that she was born to be a mother.

This remembering was so powerful for me 💚 It was yet another reminder that my brain plays tricks on me. 
.
I also want to add that not everyone has a life “before” OCD. Some remember having OCD for as long as they’ve lived.
.
And for those who remember their life before OCD, it can be powerful to be reminded of what we loved and how we felt and our values and joys before the onset of it.

“You are a work of art yourself,” said the older museum attendant as I was admiring art. “Very womanly.”
.
He wasn’t creepy. It wasn’t cat-cally. The older gentleman bowed as he said it, and I got the sense that he really was admiring art in me.
.
It got me thinking. About thinness as the ideal in America and how that isn’t the case in other parts of the world. About Renaissance and Baroque art that was deeply admired, featuring women with curves and jiggle and rolls.
.
Now, I don’t think there is a body that makes a woman “womanly”. But I do know that what America and some of the western world sees as the epitome of beauty for a woman (as adjacent to thinness as possible) is not universal. I do know that thin is not synonymous with beauty.
.
We don’t owe anyone beauty. There is no “right” or “perfect” body. ~And~ hearing this man genuinely find curves beautiful was a beautiful reminder in a world that values thinness.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

People often use “accept uncertainty” and “stop performing compulsions” interchangeably, which can be so harmful!
.
They are two different things. And we don’t always need to accept uncertainty to recover from OCD or to stop performing compulsions.
.
Telling someone to accept uncertainty when they know they’re not that thing (a kiIIer, a p3d, etc.) is harmful.
.
We can both know we are not what OCD is saying ~and~ choose to stop performing compulsions.
.
Language matters 🤍 Questions for me? I’ll answer below 👇🏼
.
Disclaimer: Some people with OCD lack insight. OCD can make us doubt what we know. Treatment can help us get to a place of knowing and trusting. It’s not that we must know these things immediately. OCD can make us doubt. This post is about accepting uncertainty and response prevention being 2 different things.
.

Su*cidal OCD is very misunderstood and different than su*cidal ideation 📢
.
People with su*cidal OCD experience unwanted intrusive thoughts about su*cide that are so distressing to them because they do NOT want to dle.
.
The person with OCD performs compulsions to ensure that d€ath never happens. It’s the opposite of developing a plan to dle or having intent to do so.
.
The person with OCD gets relentless thoughts about su*cide and can’t understand why their brain is doing this when they don’t want to dle or think about d€ath.
.
Clinicians who don’t understand OCD might misdiagnose su*cidal OCD as su*cidal ideation. Some with OCD have been wrongly hospitalized.
.
Knowing the difference between the two is key 💜
.

Every day is spooky with OCD ☠️ Let’s talk Harm OCD 👇🏼
.
Harm OCD is a nickname for people with OCD whose obsessions (repetitive, unwanted thoughts, images, and urges) center on vi0l3ntly harming others or themselves.
.
As with any obsession, harm obsessions are egodystonic: opposite to a person’s values, desires, and self-concept. The person experiencing them does NOT want to harm anyone and is extremely distressed by the recurring thoughts and images.
.
People with OCD perform compulsions (physical or mental acts) in response to obsessions to alleviate anxiety, prevent something bad from happening, etc. They do NOT want the obsessions to come true, so much so that they perform excessive and time-consuming compulsions to ensure they do not.
.
Common harm OCD compulsions:
💥 Throwing away all sharp objects
💥 Avoiding driving or other situations in which they could “snap” and cause harm
💥 Mental checking to ensure that the obsessions are scary
💥 Locking the bedroom door at night in case they sleepwalk and harm someone
💥 And so much more!
.
I don’t have enough space to list every possible symptom so don’t fret if you don’t see yours 🤍
.

When this started happening to me, I thought I was hallucinating. I thought I was experiencing psychosis. The intrusive images and mental movies were SO vivid and terrifying.
.
I later came to find out that they were a symptom of my OCD and that I was not hallucinating. I was experiencing intrusive images internally.
.
If you experience this, you’re not alone 💚 It can feel scarier than a thought because you’re actually seeing it play out in your mind. This can be traumatizing.
.
I was 100% traumatized by OCD and intrusive images.
.
It’s important to note: an intrusive image or mental movie that happens to you is different than you hypothesizing and imagining as a mental compulsion.
.

My brain said let’s give her the ✨big daddy✨ In all seriousness, I always wished for another OCD theme. I do not believe that all OCD themes are the same in regard to shame and stigma, access to treatment, etc. 
.
This does not mean I’m saying POCD is harder to treat and that something like contamination OCD isn’t difficult to live with.
.
But there are realities to living with a taboo theme like POCD, which is (in my opinion) the most stigmatized obsessional theme:
- Not being able to share freely (It’s far less stigmatizing to tell someone you fear contamination than you are having unwanted s€xuaI thoughts about children)
- Fear, shame and stigma stopping you from seeking help; I was TERRIFIED that a professional would report me or call the police. It stopped me from opening up about my symptoms for a while.
- The added layer of shame that must be worked through with taboo obsessions
- OCD attacking your identity and who you are; not something external
- And so much more!
.
Wishing for another OCD theme when you have POCD or another taboo obsession isn’t something to be ashamed of. It’s not disregarding the suffering of others. It’s validating your reality.
.
Love y’all 🩷

@kayarose was the first person I ever told about my OCD. We were driving to the Halloween store in Los Angeles, accompanied by my purse filled with sticky notes of the intrusive thoughts I wrote down in therapy as a defusion exercise.
.
I was nervous someone would find the sticky notes. I’m sure I was nervous to tell her. But I did and I don’t think there was a better first person I could’ve told.
.
There was no judgment. No shame. No stigma. No “do you actually want to do that?” There was a lot of openness and empathy. Unwavering understanding. I will never forget her saying, “Sometimes I get odd thoughts too. Like at the coffee shop I think I could just throw my hot coffee on a grandpa.”
.
We have had twists and turns in our 10 years of friendship, ups and downs as we have navigated our 20s, but the downs were never because of my OCD. 19-year-old Alegra didn’t think it was possible to have people love her with OCD, and Kaya really set the stage.
.
I’m so glad I moved into a Los Angeles apartment at 20 with 5 other ladies who also changed my life ❤️ (Bad B*tches Brigade 4eva) —> 3rd photo

I have OCD and it has NOTHING to do with contamination and germs. Many people live with OCD and don’t have contamination fears because 📣OCD does not just entail contamination obsessions📣
.
Contamination obsessions are the most publicly recognized manifestation of OCD, but they actually make up a small sliver of obsessional themes.
.
Common obsessional fears:
🍰 What if I’m attracted to family members, animals, kids?
🍰 What if I snap and harm my spouse?
🍰 What if I hit someone driving and don’t remember?
🍰 What if I’m not actually a lesbian and I’m lying to everyone?

Mental compulsions of OCD can be habitual 🫠 You perform them so often that you jump into them without much conscious awareness, which can leave you feeling hopeless.
.
You might be asking, how do I stop something that I don’t even know I’m doing? That I don’t have awareness of?
.
We can use mindfulness skills to create that awareness 🤯
.
We can:
1️⃣ Notice when we are performing a mental compulsion (even 20 minutes in)
2️⃣ Label it (this helps create awareness)
3️⃣ Correct (stop the mental compulsion and come back to what is helpful in the present moment)
.
This looks like:
➡️ I notice I am ruminating right now. This isn’t helpful. I’m going to stop ruminating and turn my attention back to the book I’m reading.
.
Mindfulness skills can help create awareness of mental compulsions so that we catch them more quickly and have more space in between the obsession and mental compulsion to decide if we are going to perform the compulsion.
.

The OCD haze is real 😮‍💨 Your brain is so gripped into an obsession, your fight-or-flight is kicking in, you feel disconnected from what you’ve known about yourself and the world, and the obsessions feels SO. REAL.
.
I have been there, a time or two (aka a hundred thousand). The OCD feels so real and your instinct is to buy into it because it feels different. It feels as if it could actually be true, as if you could actually like it.
.
But here’s the thing: the brain and body lie to us.
.
Just because something is feeling real doesn’t mean that it is. Just because your brain is telling you that there is danger this time doesn’t mean that there is.
.
OCD can feel real for a number of reasons:
- The brain and body misfiring
- Compulsions keeping us absorbed in an obsession
- Fight-or-flight being confused with desire, excitement, enjoyment
- The visceral intrusive images and thoughts
- And so much more!
.
When we are in this state, we want to reach for logic. We want logic to cure us but it’s hard to connect to logic when the nervous system is activated and flooded. It’s hard to connect to logic when you’re hooked into an obsession.
.
This doesn’t mean that logic doesn’t exist. It does! It doesn’t mean that it’s not helpful to look at how we’ve gotten hooked into the obsession. It can be.
.
It means that trying to use logic to get out of the obsession while OCD is loud is likely unhelpful at best and harmful at worst.
.
When this happens to me, it truly feels like my brain is glitching and I know that I need to ride the wave until the brain calms down. I see it for what it is (OCD feeling real) and do not engage with it no matter how real it feels. I know OCD’s patterns and so can you.
.

Did you really let your intrusive thoughts win? Or did you act on impulse? Those are two very different things 📣
.
Is this important? YES! It’s not merely a joke. It can have actual consequences for people who experience terrifying intrusive thoughts as I’ve described in the video.
.
Intrusive thoughts are distressing, UNWANTED thoughts that a person does not desire acting on. Calling impulsive behavior an intrusive thought wrongly leads people to believe that folks with unwanted intrusive thoughts act on them.
.
Impulsive behavior (acting hastily without thinking it through to obtain possible immediate gratification) is different than experiencing a terrifying thought you’d never want to act on.

Not being close to one’s family is not a red flag 🚩 A red flag is a behavior or trait that can signal danger in a relationship or partner.
.
Not being close to one’s family is not dangerous. It might actually be the safest thing for that person if they have an ab***ve, toxic family.
.
Removing oneself from unhealthy family dynamics can be a green flag for the person who desires safety for oneself and one’s partner/children.
.
It can be a ~preference~ to date someone who is close to their family, but it’s not a red flag if someone is not.
.
We can’t help the family we were born into and we can’t assume that everyone has a safe, healthy, loving family.
.

OCD can make driving incredibly anxiety-provoking and time-consuming for those with driving obsessions 🤯
.
Common obsessions:
🚗 What if I hit a person and didn’t know?
🚗 What if I snap and swerve off the road?
🚗 What if I intentionally run people over?
🚗 What if I jump out of the car while driving?
🚗 What if that bump was a child?
🚗 And so much more!
.
Common compulsions:
🚙 Turning the car around to check (often repeatedly)
🚙 Mentally reviewing driving experiences
🚙 Avoidance of driving in certain situations or altogether
🚙 Checking police and traffic reports
🚙 Checking the vehicle for scratches, blood, bumps, etc.
🚙 And so much more!
.
People with OCD doubt what they know. The person knows that they didn’t see a person fly through their windshield, but the “what if” takes over. They know they are not su*c*dal and wouldn’t swerve the car, but doubt that (because of the intensity of the thoughts and images, for example)
.
If this is you, you’re not alone ❤️ It is a common manifestation of OCD and it can be treated effectively with evidence-based treatment for OCD like Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP)

This is a hard truth, but one that will set you free 🩷 It is a truth that changed the course of my recovery journey in a profound way.
.
I ✨get✨ wanting OCD to leave us alone on special occasions. I get wanting to eat that Christmas pie and open gifts and spend time with loved ones without your brain feeding you with scary thoughts and uncomfortable feelings.
.
I used to resist so heavily when I had a special moment coming up, but my therapist helped me realize that it only made me suffer more. She helped me recognize that we can’t wish our thoughts and feelings away and the more we try, the more pain we are in.
.
When I started to allow my brain to produce the scary thoughts, without judgment and without resistance, I felt freer. I learned that I could experience joy and big moments ~while~ the thoughts and feelings were there.
.
Was it ideal? Of course not! Did I have to be realistic? I sure did.
.

I didn’t one day start struggling with an inability to accept uncertainty about who I am. My brain broke one day and I started experiencing relentless intrusive thoughts and images on repeat that TERRIFIED me. Living with this new brain was the problem, not uncertainty.
.
The obsessions, at times, caused me doubt what I knew about myself. But that’s the difference: doubting what I KNEW of me vs. having to tolerate uncertainty about something I didn’t know.
.
This is not to say that tolerating uncertainty when we don’t have the information isn’t helpful or that it’s not helpful in OCD treatment. It can be, but it wasn’t necessary or helpful for me.
.
I wanted to share this perspective, as I often see “accept the uncertainty” as the OCD cure and that’s not always helpful.

Two things can exist at once: Danae’s work is wonderful and necessary AND @thetimes can do better than feature a thin, toned, white woman as the face of a movement that was created by and for marginalized, oppressed folks (fat, Black, queer folks).

.

.
This is a critique of the systems that continue to perpetuate thinness and whiteness as the norm.

This is how my OCD manifested: rapid fire intrusive thoughts that replayed over and over again. They were the scariest thoughts I could ever think and I didn’t want to be thinking them.
.
My brain kept producing them, like a broken record, and I had to walk through the world with a terrorizing soundtrack in my head. I couldn’t turn my brain off like a radio. I couldn’t turn the volume down. I was subjected to torture.
.
This is how OCD manifests for many: repetitive, unwanted intrusive thoughts of a taboo nature (s € x, vi0Ience, etc.)
.
Doesn’t everyone get intrusive thoughts? Yes, everyone has an unwanted thought from time to time. For people with OCD, they tend to stick. The person experiences obsessional doubt and performs compulsions (mental or physical) in response to them. The symptoms impair their functioning.
.
If this is you, you’re not alone 🖤 Your scary thoughts do not define you. They are not you. They are opposite to your values and desires and that’s why they scare you so much.
.
If this is you, you’re one of the strongest people to exist. Period.
